bjorn3 commented on cae5232:

This is wrong. i128 is supposed to be stored as two i64, just like i64 is supposed to be stored as two i32 on 32bit systems. Storing it in a vector register makes it a lot harder to generate efficient math operations for i128.

uweigand commented on e694fb1:

It looks like this commit broke by (still out-of-tree) IBM Z (s390x) port.

The problem is that in this port I'm not at all using the IFLAGS type or any of the instructions associated with it (like ifcmp or selectif), because it doesn't really match the ISA. Instead, I'm leaving everything to use the "default" operations like icmp and select, and use the input matching infrastructure of the new backend to combine those effciently.

That used to work fine, since common code never introduced any use of IFLAGS unless the back end defines the TargetIsa::uses_cpu_flags() callback to return true, which I'm not doing. But this commit now introduces an unconditional use of IFLAGS across all targets. Was this intended?

cfallin commented on e694fb1:

Hmm, no, sorry, that wasn't an intended effect. To be honest I wasn't aware that a backend implementation without IFLAGS was an option allowed by the API; I suppose this wasn't caught because the (old-style) x86 backend, and all of the new backends, do support IFLAGS; in other words nothing in-tree depends on the alternative path.

Note however that the choice to use selectif (vs. select) was sort-of forced by compatibility with the old x86 backend, because select was not being lowered to a conditional move, which we need for the mitigation. So changing things around to avoid use of flags would require additional work there.

It seems the lowest-overhead fix is simply to disable the mitigation when uses_cpu_flags() returns false; this maintains the status quo for your backend (there was no Spectre mitigation at all before this patch). Thoughts?

uweigand commented on e694fb1:

I'm actually a bit confused about the status of IFLAGS with new backends; while it is true that both aarch64 and x64 support the IFLAGS type and have some lowering for flags instructions, I don't actually see any code that would ever generate those instructions. The uses_cpu_flags() function returns false for new backends (and even if it didn't, there's still an extra !is_mach_backend guard in do_postopt). Am I missing something here?

cfallin commented on e694fb1:

The new backends are written to handle IFLAGS-using instructions, but a quick sanity check shows that at least the wasm crate is not generating them (I inserted panics at brif, selectif, trueif, trapif); this is consistent with your observations. The general philosophy we took was to fill out implementations for all opcodes, and ensure they are tested in our filetests at least. That said, the main codegen path pattern-matches e.g. brnz on icmp directly. So in a hypothetical System Z port using the new backend infrastructure, it seems that you could get away with avoiding IFLAGS altogether, modulo the Spectre mitigation. This makes me think that we should probably retire this part of the CLIF definitions once we retire the old backend. @sunfishcode, @julian-seward1, @bnjbvr might have more thoughts?

uweigand commented on e694fb1:

So in a hypothetical System Z port using the new backend infrastructure, it seems that you could get away with avoiding IFLAGS altogether, modulo the Spectre mitigation.

Yes, that's exactly what I'm doing, and that works by now well enough that it passes a complete wasmtime "cargo test" including the full wasm spec testsuite ...

sunfishcode commented on e694fb1:

Yes; brif, selectif etc. are only produced by postopt by pattern-matching brnz+icmp sequences, and target-specific legalizer rules. The documentation recommends frontends avoid using them, and they're tricky to use because one has to manually avoid letting the flags get clobbered. So I agree we should remove them when we can!

julian-seward1 commented on e694fb1:

Indeed, there was some discussion at least between Chris/Ben/me at some point, about removing CLIF's concept of condition-code values completely, once the old backend is removed. I think it was generally agreed that this would be a useful simplication.

sunfishcode commented on d51ffe8:

This can use .entries() instead of .read_dir(Path::new(".")). Open to suggestions on better names for that function :-).

sunfishcode commented on d51ffe8:

Unfortunately it's not always true; if the directory lacks search ("x") permission, we may be able to open it but not readdir in it.

sunfishcode commented on d51ffe8:

Is there a reason this readdir function doesn't take a path? Does the caller always open a new Dir?

I ask because in the case where the path is not ., it should always be possible to do metadata() on path/.. to obtain the inode number, and in the case where the path is ., we might do what POSIX does in the root directory: have a .. with the same inode as ..

pchickey commented on d51ffe8:

The only reason WasiDir::readdir doesn't take a path is because wasi_snapshot_preview1::readdir does not take one. If we want to change that (probably should?) in wasi, then we can generalize this code, but it will always be called with path=. for now.

That inode trick sounds good to me, I'll put it in.

codelings-net commented on 0e41861:

I love this feature, thank you so much!

It really helps with this crazy idea I'm working on: making random changes to wasm code and trying to get it to evolve. I've run into lots of infinite loops, as you can imagine, and using a timer is rather crude - and more importantly I've had to kill the whole process, so I couldn't tell whether it was on the right track apart from the infinite loop. This feature turns infinite loops from a massive headache into 'good progress, now all we need is a counter'. Could make a huge difference, so I'm properly excited.
